In this proclamation, President Barack Obama declares November 2013 as National Diabetes Month in the United States. The proclamation highlights the impact of diabetes on the country, with over 25 million Americans living with the disease and many more undiagnosed. The proclamation emphasizes the need to combat diabetes by supporting those living with the illness, honoring professionals and advocates involved in the fight against diabetes, and raising awareness about prevention and treatment. It also mentions the serious complications that can arise from diabetes, such as heart disease, stroke, kidney failure, and blindness. The proclamation emphasizes the importance of preventive measures and encourages Americans to talk to their healthcare providers about steps they can take to prevent or manage diabetes. The Affordable Care Act is mentioned as a support system for Americans with diabetes, ensuring that no one can be denied health insurance based on their diagnosis. The National Diabetes Prevention Program and the National Diabetes Education Program are highlighted as initiatives aimed at preventing and delaying the onset of the disease. The proclamation also mentions First Lady Michelle Obama's Let's Move! initiative, which addresses the rise in childhood obesity and its connection to Type 2 diabetes. The proclamation concludes by calling on all Americans and various organizations to participate in activities that raise awareness about diabetes and help prevent, treat, and manage the disease.